t 1345–1379","1345–1379":"1345–1379","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1347–Female":"1347–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1367–1420":"1367–1420","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","1321–1370":"1321–1370","1320–1400":"1320–1400","about 1370":"about 1370","1370":"1370","1347":"1347","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1321":"1321","1420":"1420","       1378":"1378","1320":"1320","about 1345":"about 1345","about 1367":"about 1367","about 1355":"about 1355","Y Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","of Betham, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Beetham, Westmorland, England":"Beetham, Westmorland, England","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Beetham Castle, Westmorland, England":"Beetham, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Betham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Beetham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beetham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Beetham in Westmorland, probably named from a plural form, <i>bjóthum</i>, of the Old Norse element <i>bjóth</i> ‘embankment, table’, i.e. ‘(place near) the embankments’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Betham was born about 1345, in Westmorland, England, his father, Sir Ralph de Betham knt., was 25 and his mother, Cecilia Sands, was 27. He had at least 2 sons with Maud N. He died in 1379, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 35."},"et":{"about 1345–1379":"umbes 1345–1379","1345–1379":"1345–1379","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1347–Female":"1347–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1367–1420":"1367–1420","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1321–1370":"1321–1370","1320–1400":"1320–1400","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1370":"1370","1347":"1347","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1367":"1367","1345":"1345","1321":"1321","1420":"1420","       1378":"1378","1320":"1320","about 1345":"umbes 1345","about 1367":"umbes 1367","about 1355":"umbes 1355","Y Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","of Betham, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beetham, Westmorland, England":"Beetham, Westmorland, England","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Som